<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Interactive Teletext" class="currentChild" href="Interactive_Teletext">Interactive Teletext</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A two-way transmission of <a title="teletext" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/teletext">teletext</a> using a <a title="cable television network" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/cable_television_network">cable television network</a> to transmit information <em>to</em> the viewer, and a simultaneous telephone-line connection to transmit information <em>from</em> the user. Essentially, the viewer sees text and graphics on the television screen, and the keypad on a telephone is used to control the display of that text and graphics, as well as respond to its content (such as in the ordering of products and services). See also <a title="Teletext" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Teletext">Teletext</a>. <em>Interactive teletext</em> is often abbreviated <a title="i.txt" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/i.txt">i.txt</a>, and is also known as <a title="Interactive Videotext" href="Interactive_Videotext">interactive videotext</a>. 
</p>
